[2]
Date: Tue 7 Mar 2006 6:42 PM
From: Ron Thornton<Ron.Thornton@maf.govt.nz>
Via: Howard Pharo <Howard.Pharo@maf.govt.nz>

PMWS was first notified in New Zealand in late 2003. MAF
investigation of the disease led to the conclusion that it was
widespread. It was considered ineradicable due to the wide
distribution and limitations in diagnosing the syndrome.
The pig industry developed a control plan for PMWS in the North
Island. No South Island cases were confirmed at the time.
MAF maintained movement controls to allow industry time to work
through its control options.
5 properties in the South Island have signs suggestive of PMWS. The
investigation on one of the earlier farms has not yet confirmed PMWS.
The industry and their pig experts have been involved in
investigating the other 4 farms, as it has been agreed that industry
will manage PMWS within New Zealand but MAF will provide assistance
as required.
--
Ron Thornton,
Team Manager (Animal Kingdom)
Surveillance and Incursion Response
Biosecurity New Zealand
Ministry of Agriculture & Forestry
Wellington, New Zealand.
<Ron.Thornton@maf.govt.nz>
[Postweaning multisystemic wasting syndrome (PMWS) of swine, due to
porcine circovirus type 2 (PCV2), was identified in western Canada in
1991; however, retrospective studies from several countries indicate
PMWS was present in the previous decade. PMWS is distributed
worldwide and most swine-producing countries report variable
prevalence of the disease. The primary manifestations are poor growth
rate, ill thrift, and/or wasting. PMWS often occurs after weaning in
pigs 4-14 wks old. The disease can also be seen in older pigs,
particularly finishing pigs that weigh 45-70 kg. Morbidity is
typically 5-20 percent among cohorts in the nursery or finishing
stages. Mortality in swine that show signs of PMWS often is above 50
percent. In addition to death loss, PMWS in finishing pigs may
prevent, or substantially delay, affected pigs from reaching market
weight, which can result in economic loss for the producer.
For more details go to:
<http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/54200.htm>
- Mod.MHJ]
